    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at our quarterly reports for the electronics warehouse and our shrinkage numbers are way higher than usual. i need to figure out how this unexpected loss is going to mess with our inventory turnover ratio. can you show me how to factor shrinkage into that calculation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Shrinkage, which is the inventory loss due to theft or damage, directly impacts the *Cost of Goods Sold* (COGS) in your calculations. To factor it in, you need to adjust your reported inventory values to reflect the actual amount available for sale. This means your effective COGS will be higher than what your standard sales minus ending inventory suggests, which will consequently lower your inventory turnover ratio.\n\nThe standard formula is: $\\text{Inventory Turnover} = \\frac{\\text{COGS}}{\\text{Average Inventory}}$. When shrinkage is high, you must increase the numerator (COGS) to accurately reflect the cost of the goods that left the warehouse.",
      "source": "target",
